3.	Open Source freedoms\
\pard\pardeftab720\li340\ri-1446\sl230

\b0 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw1
Free and Open Source Software (FOSS)
\fs10 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw1
 
\fs21 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw1
\super 20\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw1
\nosupersub  is by now an established fact, a thriving industry. Almost two thirds of web servers run on Linux, while three quarters of web servers use Open Source Apache to respond to browser requests. 70 percent of web browsers are either completely Open Source (Firefox) or share large parts of their codebase with Open Source products (Google Chrome), and use an Open Source layout engine for rendering HTML \'96 Gecko in the case of Firefox, WebKit in the case of Google Chrome and Apple\'92s Safari. Other notable examples include server-side programming languages (such as PHP) and content management systems (Drupal, Joomla, WordPress). Contributors to FOSS are not just loony coders; Benkler notes that \'93just under 40 percent of firms engaged in software development report spending development time on developing and contributing to FOSS software.\'94
\fs10 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw1
 
\fs21 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw1
\super 21\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw1
\nosupersub  \
\pard\pardeftab720\li340\fi-340\ri-1446\sl230
\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 Free and Open Source Software is built on two propositions; a legal proposition which obliterates legal defaults of \'91intellectual property\'92 protection, and a social proposition which creates a practice for peer-to-peer collaboration.\
The \'91four freedoms\'92 described for Free and Open Source Software \super 22\nosupersub  form a radical counterpoint to the software industry\'92s narrow end-user license agreements (EULAs). EULAs are based on the assumption \'96 readily confirmed by legislators and judges \'96 that software code is a form of artistic expression, and stipulate that users may only use a copy of the software for defined purposes; they don\'92t own it and are not allowed to share or copy it, often not even to re-sell it. Free software licenses on the other hand allow users to use the software for any purpose, to study it, copy and spread it (gratis or paid), and also to \'91fork\'92 it, i.e. to build new derivative software on top of it.\
The freedoms of Open Source clearly state that any piece of code may be used for any purpose whatsoever \'96 even commercial purposes. Therefore Open Source is diametrically opposite to incumbent business models of mass production, which are based on the concept of scarcity and on the assumption that only the owner of intellectual property should be allowed to exploit it commercially. Scarcity is a natural given for original paintings in oil on canvas; a business model based on selling the original makes a lot of practical sense here. Additionally, the value of works of art can be \'91oligarchic\'92 or \'91positional\'92, drawing their value from social scarcity: any multiplication of the work of art would destroy that which made it desirable in the first place. \super 23\nosupersub  On the other hand, in the case of anything digital \'96 where the copy is absolutely identical to the original, to the extent that the two cannot be distinguished, and where the original remains unaltered by the copying process \'96 scarcity as the basis for a business model simply does not work, unless this scarcity is created by artificial means.\
In this sense, free software fundamentally breaks with the scarcity-based business model, effectively separating the code \'96 as the part that is easy to copy, and hence hard to protect \'96 from the whole product of a software package, which also includes packaging, installation, maintenance, documentation, training, configuration and customisation. Similar approaches have been developed in the field of cultural production, with the set of Creative Commons licenses which reverse the content scarcity created artificially by copyright. Yet not all Creative Commons licenses actually make the content freely available according to the spirit of free culture (which would mirror the software freedoms); particularly clauses prohibiting commercial use or derivative works make the corresponding Creative Commons-licensed work actually \'91non-free\'92.\
