\b \cf0 6.	\'91Open\'92 in art education and practice\
\pard\pardeftab720\li340\ri-1446\sl230

\b0 \cf0 Academic art education, particularly drawing and design, underwent a utilitarian reorientation during the industrial revolution. A famous example is the Government School of Design in London which was founded in 1837 and eventually became the Royal College of Art, located in London\'92s South Kensington district. The \'91South Kensington system\'92 in art education was part of a general drive toward the \'93development of human capital to produce art goods and manufactures that could expand both economic and symbolic capital for nation-states.\'94 \super 36\nosupersub  \
\pard\pardeftab720\li340\fi-340\ri-1446\sl230
\cf0 The curriculum of art education has since undergone many changes: an emphasis on creative self-expression in the 1920s; an emulation of scientific method, focused on making art education more rigorous, since the 1960s (particularly in the United States, as \'91discipline-based art education\'92); and a more critical, socially reconstructionist or issues-based approach since the 1990s,
\fs10  
\fs21 \super 37\nosupersub  moving towards what Dennis Atkinson calls a \'93negotiated and transformative curriculum.\'94 \super 38\nosupersub  However, even in this negotiated approach, Eve Harwood argues that the voice of the student is still notably absent, and teaching at times lacks concern for students\'92 aspirations.
\fs10  
\fs21 \super 39\nosupersub  Art education in Europe and North America has followed the development of industrialisation, the rise of capitalism and the emergence of the middle class; economic and cultural imperialism and globalisation have led to an almost worldwide dissemination of this utilitarian mode of art education.
\fs6  
\fs21 \super 40\nosupersub  Following Greil Marcus\'92 line of argument, there have been only a few movements in Western art \'96 Dada, Situationism, Punk Rock \'96 that were innovative enough to break with this status quo.
\fs10  
\fs21 \super 41\nosupersub \
\pard\pardeftab720\li340\fi-340\ri-1389\sl230
\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw1
Felix Stalder adds to this list the artistic Internet experiments of the mid-1990s. As \'93cultures without commodity\'94 these movements challenged the utilitarian \'93commodity culture\'94; Stalder argues
\fs10 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw1
 
\fs21 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw1
\super 42\kerning1\expnd0\expndtw1
\nosupersub  that intellectual property law needed to be adapted (or rather: dealt with differently), and that the organisation of cultural industries needed to be challenged. Traditional artistic production and monetisation always emphasised individual authorship and the production of unique objects, treating creativity as a scarce resource \'96 hence the need to render the \'91intellectual property\'92, the product of creativity, equally scarce.\
\pard\pardeftab720\li340\fi-340\ri-1446\sl230
\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 However, \'93cultures without commodity\'94 treated creativity as an abundant resource. Authorship moved away from individuals and toward groups, networks and communities. Boundaries between artists and audiences became blurred, the (creative) processes were organised as networks rather than as traditional hierarchies. These networks extended beyond the relatively small, personal scale and became \'93capable of structuring major collective, or better, connective undertakings.\'94 \super 43\nosupersub \
