\b \cf0 7.	Open design between sharing and protecting\
\pard\pardeftab720\li340\ri-1446\sl230

\b0 \cf0 Open design can be understood as extending the tradition of Dada, Situationism, Punk Rock and the artistic Internet experiments of the mid-1990s. Also, it purports to be to design what Open Source is to software.
\fs10  
\fs21 \super 44\nosupersub  Accordingly open design, like free software, has two important facets. On one hand it is often primarily discussed in terms of licensing: how can the protection of rights be overturned to allow use, study, sharing and \'91forking\'92 of designs? On the other hand, open design also denotes a certain strand of practice in the field of design: how can the design process become more collaborative?\
\pard\pardeftab720\li340\fi-340\ri-1446\sl230
\cf0 When discussing the legal facet of design, in terms of licenses to \'91free\'92 design, it is often naively assumed that design, like software, can (only) be covered by copyright. Yet design is more diverse than software, and falls under various types of intellectual property protection \'96 even varying from country to country.
\fs10  
\fs21 \super 45\nosupersub  The pragmatic approach is to distribute blueprints of open designs (which presumably are indeed covered by copyright) with Creative Commons licenses \'96 typically requiring attribution, often with the share-alike requirement, and customarily prohibiting commercial use and reuse (known as the CC BY-NC-SA license).\
Crucially, such distribution licences are quite the opposite of \'91free\'92, as they severely restrict the \'91free\'92 use of the corresponding designs. Open Source fundamentalists may well accuse such practices of taking a free ride on the Open Source bandwag-on, as the Open Source label certainly confers a certain degree of \'91coolness\'92 within some circles of our gadget-crazy world. Designers would argue that they simply want to get their fair share if somebody else makes big money with their designs \'96 hence the \'91non-commercial\'92 clause.
\fs10  
\fs21 \super 46\nosupersub  It seems then that these designers adhere to the incumbent model of physical and artificial scarcity \'96 of a producer buying their design, selling it to the masses, and paying the designer a \'91fair share\'92 in the form of royalties.\
Finally, it is important to note that not all design disciplines have a strong tradition of intellectual property, and that not all designers cling to protection of intellectual property rights \'96 much to the disdain of policy makers as well as the intellectual property lobby.
\fs10  
\fs21 \super 47\nosupersub  In fashion design, for example, copying appears to promote rather than deter innovation; \super 48\nosupersub  other examples include hairstyles, perfume, magic tricks and fireworks displays.
\fs10  
\fs21 \super 49\nosupersub  In these cases, there seems to be no need for \'91opening\'92 design, at least not in legal terms.\
